<ns4905:section xmlns:ns4905="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.lang.basicLanguage.constants">
    <ns4906:title xmlns:ns4906="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Constants</ns4906:title>
    <ns4907:para xmlns:ns4907="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">The support for constants in Java is not as mature as that provided by C++. Still, in Java
        one can define local constants, constant method arguments and constant data members of a
        class. The keyword used for constants is <ns4908:literal xmlns:ns4908="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">final</ns4908:literal>.
        Constants must have a type in Java. To declare a double-precision floating point constant
        for <ns4909:literal xmlns:ns4909="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">PI</ns4909:literal> in Java, use the statement</ns4907:para>
    <ns4910:para xmlns:ns4910="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        <ns4911:programlisting xmlns:ns4911="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
final double PI = 3.1415926;
        </ns4911:programlisting>
    </ns4910:para>
</ns4905:section>